The '''Fembot Collective''' is an international collective of feminist media activists, artists, producers, and scholars that publishes the academic journal ''[[#Ada: A Journal of Gender, New Media, and Technology|Ada: A Journal of Gender, New Media, and Technology]]''.<ref name = Bitch>{{cite news|last1=Rhee|first1=Margaret|title=Hacking Feminism|url=http://bitchmagazine.org/post/fembot-collective-profile-tech-and-feminism|accessdate=28 March 2015|work=Bitch Magazine|date=17 March 2015}}</ref> Fembot has been a catalyst for multiple large scale feminist digital projects, providing the digital and social infrastructure for [[FemTechNet]],<ref>{{cite web|title=About the [FemTechNet] DOCC|url=http://cyberhouse.arted.psu.edu/DOCC/contact.html|website=Pennsylvania State University DOCC|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=LoshFemTechNet>{{cite book|last1=Losh|first1=Elizabeth|title=The War on Learning: Gaining Ground in the Digital University|date=2014|publisher=MIT Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=0262323265|pages=146–148}}<!--|accessdate=31 March 2015--></ref> publishing the podcast series Books Aren't Dead,<ref name=StabileSawchuk>{{cite journal|last1=Stabile|first1=Carol|last2=Sawchuk|first2=Kim|title=Introduction: Conversations Across the Field|journal=Ada: A Journal of Gender, New Media, and Technology|date=2012|issue=1|doi=10.7264/N3RN35SV|url=http://adanewmedia.org/2012/11/issue1-stabile/}}</ref> and hosting collaborative [[hack-a-thon]]s and [[Wikipedia]] [[edit-a-thon]]s with ''[[Ms. (magazine)|Ms.]]'' magazine.<ref name=Ms.>{{cite news|last1=Rhee|first1=Margaret|title=Gender-Balancing Wikipedia, One Article at a Time|url=http://msmagazine.com/blog/2015/03/13/gender-balacing-wikipedia-one-article-at-a-time/|accessdate=28 March 2015|agency=Ms. Magazine|date=13 March 2015}}</ref> Although having been funded and supported by multiple institutions including [[University of Oregon School of Journalism and Communication|School of Journalism and Communication]] and the [[Center for the Study of Women in Society]] at the [[University of Oregon]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Fembot Conference: Multiplying Standpoints and Participatory Feminism|url=http://csws.uoregon.edu/fembot-unconference-multiplying-standpoints-and-participatory-feminism/|website=Center for the Study of Women in Society|publisher=University of Oregon|accessdate=28 March 2015}}</ref>, Fembot is concentrated in the University of Maryland currently.
==History== The Fembot Collective was initially developed at the University of Oregon, where it was originally a research interest group led by [[Carol Stabile]] located in the Center for the Study of Women in Society.<ref name=StabileSawchuk /> Officially founded in 2011, the group grew out of conversations about the use of [[feminist ethics]] to guide transformations in [[open access]] and [[new media]] pedagogy that began as early as 2008.<ref name=Bitch /> Early projects for Fembot included the short zine series ''Laundry Day'' edited by Carol Stabile and Chelsea Bullock, and a feminist works series that spotlighted new media artists and critics.<ref name=StockingsCrush>{{cite web|last1=Ekpo|first1=Patricia|title=Currently Crushing On: Fembot Collective|url=http://bluestockingsmag.com/2013/03/22/currently-crushing-on-fembot-collective/|work=Blue Stockings Magazine}}</ref> Fembot launched its first issue of ''Ada: A Journal of Gender, New Media, and Technology'' in November 2012.<ref name=NovLaunchSOJC>{{cite web|publisher=University of Oregon School of Journalism & Communication |title=Research Newsletter |url=http://journalism.uoregon.edu/research-newsletter/11-0/ |accessdate=31 March 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140920221752/http://journalism.uoregon.edu/research-newsletter/11-0/ |archivedate=20 September 2014 |df= }}</ref> [[File:FemBot Editathon LA 2015 1.jpg|thumbnail|Ms. FemBot edit-a-thon in Los Angeles in 2015]] Since 2015, Fembot has established a partnership with ''Ms.'' magazine around writing women academics, theorists, and athletes into Wikipedia.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rhee|first1=Margaret|title=Hacking Feminism|url=https://bitchmedia.org/post/fembot-collective-profile-tech-and-feminism|accessdate=11 March 2016|work=Bitch Magazine|date=17 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Adamovic|first1=Lea|title=Fembot Initiative to again join Wikipedia Edit-a-thon|url=https://around.uoregon.edu/content/fembot-initiative-again-join-wikipedia-edit-thon|work=Around the O|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> The organization is currently led by Carol Stabile.
==''Ada: A Journal of Gender, New Media, and Technology and Controversy''== ''Ada: A Journal of Gender, New Media, and Technology'' is a feminist open access journal published in collaboration with the Fembot Collective.<ref>{{cite web|last1=JOURNAL-TOC|title=Ada: A Journal of Gender, New Media, and Technology|url=http://www.journaltocs.ac.uk/index.php?action=search&subAction=hits&journalID=27454&userQueryID=14401&high=1&ps=30&page=1&items=0&journal_filter=0&journalby=0|website=JournalTOC:|publisher=Heriott-Watt University|accessdate=31 March 2015}}</ref> It has been housed at [[Knight Library|UO Libraries]] and now is administered through the University of Maryland. Notably, the journal challenges conventional academic journal practices by using an open peer review process.<ref name=CampusTech>{{cite news|last1=Fredette|first1=Michelle|title=Rewriting the Journal|url=http://campustechnology.com/Articles/2012/08/28/Rewriting-the-Journal.aspx?Page=1|accessdate=31 March 2015|agency=Campus Technology|issue=Academic Publishing|date=28 August 2012|ref=CampusTech}}</ref>
In 2014, [[Gamergate controversy|Gamergate]] supporters targeted ''Ada: A Journal of Gender, New Media, and Technology'' as a site of "feminist propaganda," arguing that "feminist scholars have used the journal as an outlet for propaganda, allowing them to avoid the peer review processes of traditional journals."<ref name="Inside Higher Ed">{{cite news|last1=Straumsheim|first1=Carl|title=#Gamergate and Games Research|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2014/11/11/gamergate-supporters-attack-digital-games-research-association|accessdate=31 March 2015|work=Inside Higher Education|date=11 November 2014}}</ref> In response, Fembot members and others created a bibliography of critical resources for studying the gendered dimensions of the Gamergate controversy, published by the International Communication Association.<ref name=ICA>{{cite news|last1=Chess|first1=Shira|last2=Consalvo|first2=Mia|last3=Huntemann|first3=Nina|last4=Shaw|first4=Adrienne|last5=Stabile|first5=Carol|last6=Strommer-Galley|first6=Jenny|title=GamerGate and Academia|url=http://www.icahdq.org/membersnewsletter/NOV14_ART0009.asp|accessdate=31 March 2015|agency=ICA Newsletter|issue=9|publisher=International Communication Association|date=November 2014}}</ref>
