{{Fiqh |hygiene}}
The '''ḥaiẓ''' (حيض menses) is the religious state of [[menstruation]] in [[Islam]].<ref>Ghulamali Ismail Naji  ''Family Life in Islam''  1973 Page v "The Prophet (S.A.) thereupon explained to her in clear words that the abnormal flow of blood after the scheduled period of 'Haiz' (menses) was not menstrual, detailing the fact that menstrual blood is more viscous than normal blood, during"</ref><ref>Jaffur Shurreef, Gerhard Andreas Herklots ''Islam in India'' 8171568068 Page 53  1921 "The illness at the lunar periods is expressed by ' the approach of the menses ' (haiz and), v the arrival of the season for bathing ' (nihanl diid), ' the head becoming dirty ' (sir mailil hond), ' becoming unfit for prayers ' (benamdzl dnd), "</ref> Menstruation relates to various purity related restrictions in [[Islamic sexual jurisprudence]].<ref>Majid Mohammadi ''Political Islam in Post-revolutionary Iran'' 1848852762 2015 Page 24 "in the authenticity of Islamic texts and a clerical understanding of these texts is projected to be not only a religious threat ... ̄ (the scholars of Islamic law) is not merely to teach haiz and nefa ̄s (menstruating and puerperiums, purity of women); ..."</ref><ref>Ayatullah Sayyid Abulqasim al-Khui ''Islamic Laws of Ayatullah Khui'' 1312532505  2014 "Atonement for sexual intercourse with a haiz is coined gold weighing 3.457 grams for the first part, 1.729 grams for the second part and 0.865 grams for the third part of the period of menses. For example if blood is discharged from the body of .."</ref>

Muslim women that are going through menstrual bleeding are exempt from [[Fasting in Islam|fasting]] during the [[Ramadan]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Frisk|first1=Sylva|title=Submitting to God: Women and Islam in Urban Malaysia|date=2009|publisher=NIAS Press|isbn=8776940489|page=121|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jqqBn3pqiZkC&pg=PA121|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref>

